Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Co-op Bank, Harel Freres, Kenya Power

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 
2011-03-10T13:36:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-10/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-co-op-bank-harel-freres-kenya-power.html
  Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell the
most since November 2009, dropping 2.9 percent to 71.16 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest since May 4.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index gained for first time in eight
days, climbing less than 0.1 percent to 2,006.01 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index rallied for a second day, adding 0.9 percent to 25,440.36
by 1:34 p.m. in Lagos, while the Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index declined for the first time in four days, losing 0.6
percent to 1,053.11 at 12:35 p.m. in Accra. Namibia’s
FTSE  Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  was unchanged at 822.12 at 2:36 p.m.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Co-operative Bank of Kenya Ltd. (COOP)  , the nation’s
third-biggest lender by assets, fell for a fourth day, losing 55
cents, or 2.9 percent, to 18.3 shillings. Co-op Bank, as the
lender is known, posted a 55 percent increase in full-year
profit to 1.31 shillings per share in the 12 months through
December. Estimates for earnings per share were as high as 1.41
shillings and as low as 1.08 shillings, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  “It was good growth but from a market perspective, they
did not quite meet expectations because there was over-
optimism,” George Bodo, an analyst with Nairobi-based Genghis
Capital Ltd., said in a phone interview today.    Harel Freres Ltd. (HFRERES)  , a Mauritian sugar producer,
rose the most in 11 weeks, adding 1 rupee, or 2.7 percent, to
38.5 rupees. The company, which also has interests in alcohol
and electricity production, increased its stake in Intendance
Holding Ltd. to 43.8 percent, making it the biggest shareholder
in Swan Insurance Co., the group said in an e-mailed statement
yesterday.  “It is diversifying from its core cane activities and this
could reduce its volatility of earnings going forward,” Imrith
Ramtohul, a senior investment manager at Mauritius Union
Assurance, said in a phone interview from Port Louis.  Kenya Power & Lighting Co. (KPLL KN), the East African
nation’s monopoly power distributor, fell to the lowest since
April 20, losing 1 shilling, or 4.7 percent, to 20.25 shillings.
Workers started a strike following a dispute over accounting for
expenses, company spokesman Migwi Theuri said in a phone
interview today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
